VLEWIS Hamilton was caught on camera asking NASA astronauts about the moon landing hoax as he visited the space centre.\u000a\u000aF1 world champion Hamilton was visiting the Johnson Space Centre ahead of the US GP in Austin.\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a Newly released footage shows the space-mad ace getting a first-hand look at spacesuits and getting a ride in a moon buggy.\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a Fans singled out one moment in particular in the 13 minute film however \u2013 which was filmed in 2017 and uploaded to YouTube last week by Apex One.\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a Hamilton is getting a show around a piece of the ISS, when he brings up the conspiracy theory that the moon landing was faked by NASA.\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a Britain\u2019s most successful F1 driver of all time raises the point with NASA spaceman Doug Hurley.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe big question is, there is obviously theories that you didn\u2019t land on the moon\u201d In the video, Hamilton said: \u201cThe big question is, there is obviously there\u2019s the theories that you didn\u2019t land on the moon.\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a \u201cSo why would people have that theory, or those different theories that they would come up with?\u201d\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a Hurley looks bemused and then someone off camera says to the F1 champ \u201cI am not sure why they have that theory\u201d. \u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a F1 fans were divided by his comments, with some accusing him of being disrespectful and others praising him for asking tough questions.\u000a\u000aIn the clip, Hurley said: \u201cI\u2019ve always maintained it would have been harder to fake it.\u201d\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a Hamilton says \u201creally?\u201d and the NASA astronaut replies \u201coh God yeah\u201d.\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a The spaceman goes on: \u201cThink about it, it just takes one person to go spill.\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a \u201cI have had people in my own family who thought we faked it, and they came to watch me go fly in space. But not many.\u201d\u000a\u000aF1 fans flooded the comment section on YouTube \u2013 with the top comment on video being liked nearly 1,000 times saying: \u201cI can\u2019t believe he brought up the fake moon landing.\u201d\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a One said: \u201cI think he p****d them off a little bit\u201d and another added \u201cthey give him VIP treatment, then he insults them\u201d.\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a Others praised Hamilton saying \u201che has every right to question\u201d, \u201cit was pretty respectful\u201d and \u201che was very polite, it was genuine curiosity\u201d. \u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a Meanwhile dozens of other comments got into a massive bust-up of people arguing over the moon landing hoax claims.\u000a\u000aMoon landing conspiracy theories have raged since Apollo 11 landed on the lunar surface in 1969. \u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a It is a widely accepted fact and photos taken of the moon since show the landing sites, flags and footprints of the spacemen.\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a The achievement was the culmination of the space race between the US and Soviet Union \u2013 and mankind has been to the moon six times, but not since 1972.\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a Conspiracy theorists claim the evidence is an elaborate hoax, and so go as far to claim its impossible to land on the moon.\u000a\u000aHamilton is known to be a massive NASA fan, and even said the only thing he would give up F1 racing for is to go to space.\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a After his visit in 2017, he posted on Instagram he was \u201cso fricking happy\u201d about the visit and was \u201closing his sh***\u201d. \u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a He added: \u201c\u2018Guys I would happily give up my job to come work, I want to be in this pool every day and then go to space. OK?\u201d\u000a\u000a \u000a\u000a The 34-year-old has won two more world championships since the clip was filmed \u2013 and on course to become the most successful F1 driver of all time.
